column9: I assume this website will potentially spend a lot of resources and funds to provide for the user experience. On top of that, I assume, the prices of the meat are going to be much higher. Therefore, this website is probably not going to be for a wider public. Economically struggling people are going to return to the same shops to buy the (at times questionable) meat and other animal products. For me, a solution is not to add another meat producing entity, but to reduce the existing once. Meat producti has one of the largest impacts on the climate change. However, if I were to buy meat once a in a while, yes I would check that website with detailed explanations, and if I could afford, I'd purchase through it.
column11: I mostly buy products from the farmer's market, where I ask the person for info about the product. Otherwise, I don't scan, I check which country it comes from, some info about the composition. Scanning may be a good idea though.
column13: It depends, it is yes and no. Vegetables from supermarkets are mostly bad, but those from CIGL , the local greenhouse located in Esch, is much better and perfectly affordable. Moreover, they sell only seasonal vegetables, which is another way of avoiding buying products that have been shipped from countries that are miles and miles away, causing a big carbon footprint. Veggies from supermarkets, on the other hand are not always good, can last surprisingly long which is super unnatural, and they don't even taste so "real".
